President Zuma visited Alexandra along with Cooperative Governance Minister Des van Rooyen and Gauteng Premier David Makhura. JOHANNESBURG President Jacob Zuma says plans are underway to upgrade infrastructure around the Jukskei River in Alexandra to prevent a repeat of the recent disaster caused by the devastating flash floods, which ripped through homes and swept away a three-year-old girl.Zuma visited the area on Monday, along with Cooperative Governance Minister Des van Rooyen and Gauteng premier David Makhura.Government says at least 4,900 people have been affected by the floods in the province.President Zuma says plans are underway to help those left destitute by the floods. They have briefed me about what they are doing, and the plans that are being worked on and implemented. Zuma has however cautioned residents against building their homes close to river banks. To put a shack on the banks of this river is dangerous. The president says those affected by the floods will be relocated temporarily while government works with residents to find a lasting solution.WATCH: President Zuma addresses flood victims in AlexandraPresident Zuma says he empathises with the family of a three-year-old girl who was swept away by floods.Zuma visited the family of Everite Chauke who was swept away by floods on Wednesday.The president says he shares the pain of the little girl s family. We also met Mr Chauke, the father of the child looked for down the river. He told a very painful story. (Edited by Masechaba Sefularo)